* INPUT/OUTPUT *

cout --> output(print)   cout << "hello" << endl; return 0;
cin -- > input     cin >> x;   (enter some text)


* DATA TYPES *

boolean -->	1 byte -->	Stores true or false values
char -->	1 byte -->	Stores a single character/letter/number, or ASCII values
int -->	2 or 4 bytes -->	Stores whole numbers, without decimals
float -->	4 bytes -->	Stores fractional numbers, containing one or more decimals. Sufficient for storing 6-7 decimal digits
double -->	8 bytes -->	Stores fractional numbers, containing one or more decimals. Sufficient for storing 15 decimal digits

* ARITHMETIC OPERATORS *

+ --> add => a + b
- --> subtraction => a - b
* --> multiply => a * b
/ --> divide => a / b
% --> modulus => a % b (Returns the division remainder)
++ --> increment => increases value by 1
-- --> decrement => decreases value by 1

* STRINGS *
// include the string library
// #include <string>

(string greeting = "Hello";
cout << greeting;)

string f_name = Roburt, string l_name = Sulev
if we use ( + ) with 2 string will return ( string full_name = f_name + l_name => RoburtSulev

int num_a = 10, int num_b = 20 will return ( int num_c = num_a + num_b => 30

if we have string num_a= 10, string num_b = 20 will return( string num_c => 1020 )

CANT use + with int and string